</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="E491CE95FA53E2145EC56DD59A3ED917" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" type="remarks">
<paragraph id="3EB04C147945259BA12A868B2865C942" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">Remarks.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="A03560D1B1E54580F61DAAD6A3607C6B" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">
<taxonomicName id="BF27DB7627E33468B78E3B82626F3E31" class="Insecta" family="Cynipidae" genus="Rhoophilus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Rhoophilus" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Rhoophilus</taxonomicName>
is morphologically similar to the Holarctic inquiline genera 
<taxonomicName id="336884A9050CC243E179DE40BCC5D177" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Synergus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Synergus" order="Coleoptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Synergus</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="F3787B60B7EAF67A2B084520120C5E4A" authority="Dalla Torre &amp; Kieffer, 1910" authorityName="Dalla Torre &amp; Kieffer" authorityYear="1910" class="Insecta" family="Cynipidae" genus="Saphonecrus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Saphonecrus" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Saphonecrus</taxonomicName>
, and 
<taxonomicName id="3E6CD32CEBC0DF0FC661C41B6520D1B9" class="Insecta" family="Cynipidae" genus="Synophrus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Synophrus" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Synophrus</taxonomicName>
, all of which typically attack oak cynipid galls. The transverse ridges of the mesoscutum, and a mesopleuron sculptured with longitudinal ridges in 
<taxonomicName id="5B32D656734A1B30BBC0C4E247BCEA67" class="Insecta" family="Cynipidae" genus="Rhoophilus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Rhoophilus" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Rhoophilus</taxonomicName>
closely resemble characters in several species of the 
<taxonomicName id="E65ED1BD692A4AB4667C73F6DE245D46" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Synergus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Synergus" order="Coleoptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Synergus</taxonomicName>
/ 
<taxonomicName id="CCEFD5A7CD57C2943F1602C4FFCEDF52" authority="Dalla Torre &amp; Kieffer, 1910" authorityName="Dalla Torre &amp; Kieffer" authorityYear="1910" class="Insecta" family="Cynipidae" genus="Saphonecrus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Saphonecrus" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Saphonecrus</taxonomicName>
complex. A sister group relationship between 
<taxonomicName id="741BEBA61F7E06657242FEBCF50F9445" class="Insecta" family="Cynipidae" genus="Rhoophilus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Rhoophilus" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Rhoophilus</taxonomicName>
and these three oak inquiline genera was hypothesized by 
<bibRefCitation id="8E1C416A767386D0C4EC3D6F51C2625A" author="Ronquist, F" journalOrPublisher="Evolution" pageId="159" pageNumber="160" pagination="241 - 266" title="Evolution of parasitism among closely related species: Phylogenetic relationships and the origin of inquilinism in gall wasps (Hymenoptera, Cynipidae)." url="10.2307/2410091" volume="48" year="1994">Ronquist (1994)</bibRefCitation>
and 
<bibRefCitation id="0CA1A1FD30F7E94A6ECA574B7B2D0C84" author="Liljeblad, J" journalOrPublisher="Systematic Entomology" pageId="154" pageNumber="155" pagination="229 - 252" title="A phylogenetic analysis of higher-level gall wasp relationships (Hymenoptera: Cynipidae)." url="10.1046/j.1365-3113.1998.00053.x" volume="23" year="1998">Liljeblad and Ronquist (1998)</bibRefCitation>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="1BF6C89C94992511454BDDA66CF4AAFF" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="E158F9A77A6E55E71577E38BE4FE2639" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">
<pageBreakToken id="1C41CBBE794AFB6B48E1DD7FF58DE893" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" start="start">Diagnosis</pageBreakToken>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="3653EAD1661C6E2748CECB5F927F1CD1" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">
<taxonomicName id="66F7F7FCEF45EAA7378EC58323F9B122" class="Insecta" family="Cynipidae" genus="Rhoophilus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Rhoophilus" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Rhoophilus</taxonomicName>
has a closed marginal cell, a character shared with 
<taxonomicName id="363A5C0E98146C89A394E8C308D69E19" authority="Liljeblad, Nieves-Aldrey &amp; Melika, 2011" authorityName="Liljeblad, Nieves-Aldrey &amp; Melika" authorityYear="2011" class="Insecta" family="Cynipidae" genus="Qwaqwaia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Qwaqwaia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Qwaqwaia</taxonomicName>
. The areolet is triangular as in 
<taxonomicName id="DC20DC0CF4792B502EA3B9F078979905" class="Insecta" family="Cynipidae" genus="Phanacis" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Phanacis" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Phanacis</taxonomicName>
, but larger and more distinct, whereas it is elongate rhomboidal in 
<taxonomicName id="257D9A4CE9D4DE2ABBE3B57714370D4A" authority="Liljeblad, Nieves-Aldrey &amp; Melika, 2011" authorityName="Liljeblad, Nieves-Aldrey &amp; Melika" authorityYear="2011" class="Insecta" family="Cynipidae" genus="Qwaqwaia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Qwaqwaia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Qwaqwaia</taxonomicName>
. 
<taxonomicName id="E9AAD53B4493EAB36EFE609BEEDB7EE1" class="Insecta" family="Cynipidae" genus="Rhoophilus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Rhoophilus" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Rhoophilus</taxonomicName>
lacks an occipital carina as in 
<taxonomicName id="4754BA35B7984B6DF82ADD8D507F060B" class="Insecta" family="Cynipidae" genus="Phanacis" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Phanacis" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Phanacis</taxonomicName>
(present in 
<taxonomicName id="0E43AD61D8A13B37AD35948615A33014" authority="Liljeblad, Nieves-Aldrey &amp; Melika, 2011" authorityName="Liljeblad, Nieves-Aldrey &amp; Melika" authorityYear="2011" class="Insecta" family="Cynipidae" genus="Qwaqwaia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Qwaqwaia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Qwaqwaia</taxonomicName>
), but has tergites 2 and 3 fused, whereas these are free in 
<taxonomicName id="D624868D99B825CDEF8871E42BEFC505" class="Insecta" family="Cynipidae" genus="Phanacis" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Phanacis" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Phanacis</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<caption id="42534302BF985D3D5F3B3942ABE2F263" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">
<paragraph id="426D09D9A2B2B2D02A60882CFFE42BD1" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">
Figure 3. 
<taxonomicName id="F2A7AC63D51A14635B186D900F7B5AE7" class="Insecta" family="Cynipidae" genus="Rhoophilus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Rhoophilus loewi" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="loewi">Rhoophilus loewi</taxonomicName>
(South Africa). A habitus lateral view B head and mesosoma dorsal view C head, anterior view.
</paragraph>
</caption>
